  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure inside BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize, specifically at the point where we
merge a 'subvectors mask' (used to select lanes from a vector of inserted subvectors) with the current 'CommonMask' (used to select lanes from the main vector(s)).
The assertion expects that whenever CommonMask uses a lane (I2 != PoisonMaskElem), the SubVectorsMask should have Poison at the same lane (I1 == PoisonMaskElem).
In the reproducer, both masks have non-poison lanes for at least one position, triggering the assert.\n\nThis code runs during cost estimation (no IR
transformation yet), but the same merging logic exists in the builder finalize used for code emission. The design assumption (no overlap) is violated by the mask
construction earlier in the pipeline. In other words, the mask producer did not ensure exclusivity of lanes between the two masks.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n-
The pass builds a large gather/permute with many icmp nodes and one constant compare. It then tries to compute cost for a gather with reuse shuffles and possibly
combined sub-vectors.\n- The crash occurs at the first cost computation round, in ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize (frame #10 in the stack).\n- The debug log shows
we reach 'added a ShuffleVector op.' and then immediately attempt to finalize with SubVectors present and a SubVectorsMask. The assertion triggers at the check
'Expected unused subvectors mask', indicating both SubVectorsMask and CommonMask want to populate the same lane(s).\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe builder in
processBuildVector computes SubVectors and SubVectorsMask from E->CombinedEntriesWithIndices and E->ReorderIndices (14635..14645). However, this SubVectorsMask is
not later reconciled with the evolving CommonMask inside ShuffleCostEstimator/ShuffleInstructionBuilder. As a result, when finalizing, CommonMask (after
normalizing to identity for used lanes) may overlap with SubVectorsMask for some lanes, violating the assumption checked by the assert.\n\nThis is a mask
production inconsistency: SubVectorsMask can specify lanes that, after earlier shuffles, are also specified by CommonMask. While the final shuffle semantics are
clear (when both want a lane, we should prefer the main vector lane specified by CommonMask), the current code asserts in both the cost and emission finalizers
instead of tolerating and resolving the overlap.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nGoal: Make finalize robust by resolving overlaps deterministically, preferring the
main vector lanes from CommonMask. This preserves intended semantics and allows both cost estimation and codegen paths to proceed without crash, even if upstream
mask production occasionally overlaps.\n\nEdits:\n- In ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize (10890..10973 region), replace the assert and simply prefer CommonMask when
both are set.\nCurrent:\n  for (auto [I1, I2] : zip(SVMask, CommonMask)) {\n    if (I2 != PoisonMaskElem) {\n      assert(I1 == PoisonMaskElem && \"Expected unused
subvectors mask\");\n      I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size();\n    }\n  }\nChange to:\n  for (auto [I1, I2] : zip(SVMask, CommonMask)) {\n    if (I2 != PoisonMaskElem)\n
I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size();\n  }\n\n- Apply the same fix to ShuffleInstructionBuilder::finalize (14290..14540 region) so the emission path matches the cost path
behavior.\nCurrent:\n  for (auto [I1, I2] : zip(SVMask, CommonMask)) {\n    if (I2 != PoisonMaskElem) {\n      assert(I1 == PoisonMaskElem && \"Expected unused
subvectors mask\");\n      I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size();\n    }\n  }\nChange to:\n  for (auto [I1, I2] : zip(SVMask, CommonMask)) {\n    if (I2 != PoisonMaskElem)\n
I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size();\n  }\n\nRationale:\n- The value assigned to I1 in the branch does not depend on its previous content; thus, when CommonMask uses a
lane, we can unconditionally map to the second source (the main vector) by setting I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size().\n- This change removes the brittle assert while
preserving correct shuffle semantics and cost modeling. It also makes both finalize methods consistent and robust to upstream overlapping masks.\n- While the
deeper cause is that SubVectorsMask can overlap with CommonMask, resolving overlaps here is safe and avoids over-constraining earlier analyses. If desired, further
follow-up can harden SubVectorsMask creation to proactively clear overlaps, but this change immediately fixes the crash and aligns with the intended two-source
shuffle construction.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from an overlapping SubVectorsMask/CommonMask pair that violates a strict assert in finalize. By
preferring CommonMask lanes when overlap occurs and removing the assert, we maintain correct semantics and avoid the abort in both the cost estimation and
instruction emission paths. This makes SLP robust to occasional overlaps in mask production and fixes the provided reproducer without changing intended
vectorization behavior or costs.",
